on": "MEMBER", "body_html": "<p>buffers such as running_mean and running_std are essential for restoring the model function, but are not saved via parameter_dict.</p>\n<p>I think there's real value in returning a dict that saves these, and restores them back.</p>\n<p>For example, in the dcgan example, I switched to checkpointing the model's parameter dict, instead of the model itself. This is much cleaner than saving the model, because i have certain variables like nGPU that change from run to run that I dont want to save as part of the model.</p>\n<p>How should we solve this?</p>", "body_text": "buffers such as running_mean and running_std are essential for restoring the model function, but are not saved via parameter_dict.\nI think there's real value in returning a dict that saves these, and restores them back.\nFor example, in the dcgan example, I switched to checkpointing the model's parameter dict, instead of the model itself. This is much cleaner than saving the model, because i have certain variables like nGPU that change from run to run that I dont want to save as part of the model.\nHow should we solve this?", "body": "buffers such as running_mean and running_std are essential for restoring the model function, but are not saved via parameter_dict.\r\n\r\nI think there's real value in returning a dict that saves these, and restores them back.\r\n\r\nFor example, in the dcgan example, I switched to checkpointing the model's parameter dict, instead of the model itself. This is much cleaner than saving the model, because i have certain variables like nGPU that change from run to run that I dont want to save as part of the model.\r\n\r\nHow should we solve this?"}